english:
  title: Record of the Drum-Chest Studio
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When heaven and earth resound, the eight winds blow forth. When thunder and lightning drum across the sky, all things are brought to life. So too does the sage first awaken understanding in his people, then stir their virtue and bestow his grace upon them—surely there is something here to learn from. Thus the scholar, in pursuing their studies, must add the work of constant vigilance. When students first enter the academy, the great officer sounds the drum to summon them. Once assembled, they open their chests and unfold their books—this is why we speak of "drumming the chest." In doing so, we would have scholars approach their duties with reverence and obedience. As the Records say: "At the opening of studies, drum and chest are opened to instill respect for one's work."

    The drum is the instrument by which we awaken the multitude. In all military campaigns and labor, it keeps the rhythm. The chest is the scholar's keeper of necessities—within it are stored the books, brushes, and inkstones. When the drum summons forth, the chest opens, and one may measure the depth of learning and the progress made. The true scholar must review the old to understand the new, growing daily without losing sight of the path. Between motion and stillness, let diligence in study be your only concern, and surely you shall gain understanding.

    As the Records teach: "The great officer employs music to summon the scholars with drums." And again: "At dawn, the drum calls forth." Whether in welcoming students or in ritual sacrifice, the drum's voice summons the worthy. Those possessions stored within the chest—all scrolls and implements—must be kept in perfect order and scrupulously maintained. When read with diligence and studied with precision, then shall you come to know the true value of the drum-chest to the scholar. The drum stirs the heart to awakening, the chest calls forth devoted effort, until hand and foot cannot help but dance—only then is the work complete. How great is the blessing of the drum-chest!

    A few of my students of writing built their dwelling to the east of my home. Upon its completion, they named it "The Drum-Chest Studio," hoping thereby to spur themselves forward in their studies. Yet my learning is insufficient to gather true friends, and these students insist on studying under me—it is like asking the blind and deaf for sight and hearing. But know this: the path of advancement lies within yourselves alone; it cannot be sought from another. Apply yourselves with resolve.
  footnotes:
    - The "eight winds" (八風) refer to winds from the eight cardinal and intercardinal directions, representing the harmony of natural forces.
    - '"Drum-chest" (鼓篋) is a compound metaphor: the drum as a call to awakening, the chest as a repository of knowledge and tools for learning.'
    - The Records (《禮記》, Yiji) is one of the foundational Confucian texts on ritual and propriety.
    - Lee Cham employs the classical trope of false modesty when he compares himself to 'the blind and deaf,' a Confucian rhetorical gesture of humility before one's students.
